Exp 1:
Here’s how to actually do each step (with explanation + what’s happening behind the scenes) so you understand—not just copy commands.
________________________________________
🧩 Step 1 – Initialize repo & first commit
👉 What you’re doing
You are creating a local Git repository and saving your first version (commit).
Commands:
git init myproject
cd myproject
✔ Creates a folder + initializes Git (adds .git hidden folder)
________________________________________
echo "# My DevOps Project" > README.md
✔ Creates a file called README.md
________________________________________
git add README.md
✔ Moves file to staging area (ready to commit)
________________________________________
git commit -m "Initial commit: add README"
✔ Saves a snapshot (version) of your project
________________________________________
🧠 Concept (important)
•	Working directory → your files 
•	Staging area → selected files 
•	Repository → committed history 
________________________________________
🌿 Step 2 – Create a branch & make changes
👉 What you’re doing
You are creating a separate line of development (branch).
________________________________________
git checkout -b feature/hello
✔ Creates + switches to new branch
________________________________________
echo "Hello from feature branch" > hello.txt
git add hello.txt
git commit -m "feat: add hello.txt"
✔ You added a new file in this branch
✔ This commit exists only in feature/hello branch
________________________________________
🧠 Concept
•	Branch = independent version of code 
•	main → stable 
•	feature/... → new changes 
________________________________________
☁️ Step 3 – Push to GitHub & create Pull Request
👉 First, create repo on GitHub
Go to 👉 GitHub
Create repo: myproject
________________________________________
👉 Connect local repo to GitHub
git remote add origin https://github.com/<username>/myproject.git
✔ origin = nickname for your remote repo
________________________________________
👉 Push branch
git push -u origin feature/hello
✔ Uploads your branch to GitHub
✔ -u sets upstream (so next time just git push works)
________________________________________
👉 Create Pull Request (PR)
On GitHub:
•	Click Compare & pull request 
•	Add description 
•	Click Create pull request 
________________________________________
🧠 Concept
Pull Request =
👉 “Please merge my feature into main”
________________________________________
🔀 Step 4 – Merge & push main
Now you combine your feature into main.
________________________________________
git checkout main
✔ Switch back to main branch
________________________________________
git merge feature/hello
✔ Combines feature branch into main
________________________________________
git push origin main
✔ Updates GitHub main branch
________________________________________
📊 View commit history (very important)
git log --oneline --graph
Output looks like:
* abc123 feat: add hello.txt
* def456 Initial commit
✅ FIX (Choose ONE method)
________________________________________
🟢 Method 1 (Best & easiest) – Allow unrelated histories
Run this in your terminal:
git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories
👉 Then:
git checkout main
git merge feature/hello
git push origin main
✔ Now both histories will combine
✔ Pull request will work
________________________________________
🟢 Method 2 – Create PR directly (quick fix)
Your terminal already gave this link:
👉 Open:
https://github.com/Dhanyashriee/myproject/pull/new/feature/hello
✔ Click:
•	Create Pull Request 
•	Then click Merge 
