Good — now you’ve hit the next real Git concept: merge conflict. This is expected, not an error you “broke” something with.
Let’s fix it cleanly 👇
________________________________________
❗ What happened (from your screenshot)
You ran:
git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories
✔ Git tried to merge
❌ Conflict occurred in README.md
Now Git is saying:
“You must resolve conflict before doing anything else”
________________________________________
🧠 Why conflict happened
Both places changed the same file:
•	GitHub → README.md 
•	Your local → README.md 
👉 Git doesn’t know which one to keep
________________________________________
🔧 Step-by-step FIX (do exactly this)
________________________________________
🟢 Step 1 – Open the file
Open README.md in:
•	Notepad / VS Code / any editor 
You’ll see something like:
<<<<<<< HEAD
# My DevOps Project
=======
# My DevOps Project (from GitHub)
>>>>>>> main
________________________________________
🟢 Step 2 – Fix manually
👉 Choose what you want:
Example (clean version):
# My DevOps Project
❗ Remove:
•	<<<<<<< 
•	======= 
•	>>>>>>> 
________________________________________
🟢 Step 3 – Mark conflict as resolved
git add README.md
________________________________________
🟢 Step 4 – Commit merge
git commit -m "fix: resolve merge conflict in README"
________________________________________
🟢 Step 5 – Now switch branch properly
git checkout main
________________________________________
🟢 Step 6 – Merge feature branch
git merge feature/hello
________________________________________
🟢 Step 7 – Push to GitHub
git push origin main
________________________________________
❗ About your errors (explained simply)
🔴 Error:
README.md: needs merge
👉 Means conflict not solved yet
________________________________________
🔴 Error:
you need to resolve your current index first
👉 Git is blocked until conflict is fixed
________________________________________
🔴 Error:
src refspec main does not match any
👉 Happens because merge wasn’t completed
________________________________________
🧠 Important concept (exam/viva question)
👉 What is merge conflict?
When two branches modify the same file/line and Git cannot decide automatically.
________________________________________
🚀 Quick shortcut (if you want EASY way)
If you don’t care about README conflict:
git merge --abort
git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories
Then fix again properly.
________________________________________
🎯 What you should do NOW
👉 Just do:
1.	Open README.md 
2.	Remove conflict markers 
3.	Run: 
git add README.md
git commit -m "resolved conflict"
🔧 What you will see inside
You’ll see something like:
<<<<<<< HEAD
# My DevOps Project
=======
# My DevOps Project
>>>>>>> main
________________________________________
✏️ What you should do
👉 Delete ALL symbols:
•	<<<<<<< 
•	======= 
•	>>>>>>> 
Keep only:
# My DevOps Project
________________________________________
💾 Save the file
Then go back to terminal and run:
git add README.md
git commit -m "resolved merge conflict"
________________________________________
🧠 Simple understanding
•	Opening file = normal text editing 
•	Conflict markers = Git asking YOU to decide 
•	You fix → Git continues 
